"# Chapter 9 — First Macros

There's a moment, when you're learning a language, when you realize you'd like to say something the language doesn't quite let you say.

You've written `(let loop ((i 0)) (when (< i n) ... (loop (+ i 1))))` fifty times. You'd love to just write `(repeat n ...)`.

You've written `(if condition (do-a-thing))` and wished there was `(when condition (do-a-thing))` — oh wait, there is. And there's `unless` too. Whoever built the language thought of it before you.

But not every convenience made it into the base. Some had to wait for you to invent them.

In most languages that's a wall — you can't add new syntax without waiting for the language designers. In Scheme, syntax is *yours*. You can define new forms whenever you like. The tool is called a *macro*, and by the end of this chapter you'll have written several.

## What a macro actually does

A macro is a *code transformation*. When Motoi is reading your program, it hits a macro use. Before evaluating it, the macro *rewrites* the code into some equivalent code that Motoi does know how to handle. Then Motoi evaluates the rewritten version.

Concrete: suppose we define `unless` as a macro (Motoi already has it, but pretend it didn't).

```
(define-syntax unless
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ condition body ...)
     (when (not condition) body ...))))
```

Now when you write:

```
(unless raining?
  (go-outside))
```

Motoi's macro expander sees `unless` and rewrites your code into:

```
(when (not raining?)
  (go-outside))
```

Then it evaluates the rewritten version. `when` is a built-in. `not` is a built-in. Everything works.

The macro didn't add any *runtime* cost. It happened at expansion time, before evaluation. From the interpreter's point of view, `unless` never existed — it saw `when` and `not`.

## `syntax-rules` — pattern matching for code

The mechanism we're using is called `syntax-rules`. Every macro you'll write in this chapter has this shape:

```
(define-syntax NAME
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ PATTERN) TEMPLATE)
    ((_ PATTERN) TEMPLATE)
    ...))
```

- `NAME` — the macro's name.
- `syntax-rules ()` — the macro engine. The empty `()` is a list of *literal* symbols the pattern uses; usually empty.
- Each rule has a **pattern** and a **template**.
- **Pattern** — the shape of code the macro should match. `_` stands for the macro's name. Other names in the pattern become *pattern variables*.
- **Template** — the rewritten code. The pattern variables get substituted in.

Simplest macro possible:

```
(define-syntax hello
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_) (display \"hello\"))))

(hello)
```

Pattern: `(_)` — matches `(hello)` with no arguments. Template: `(display \"hello\")`. So `(hello)` expands to `(display \"hello\")`, which prints `hello`.

## A useful one: `repeat`

Here's a macro for the loop we've written over and over:

```
(define-syntax repeat
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ n body ...)
     (let loop ((i 0))
       (when (< i n)
         body ...
         (loop (+ i 1)))))))
```

Pattern: `(_ n body ...)`. `n` is a pattern variable. `body ...` is a *rest pattern* — it matches zero or more forms. That's what the `...` means: \"repeat this pattern for however many things are here.\"

Template: the loop, with `n` substituted in and `body ...` splatted out where `body ...` appears.

Now:

```
(repeat 3 (display \"tick \"))
```

Expands to:

```
(let loop ((i 0))
  (when (< i 3)
    (display \"tick \")
    (loop (+ i 1))))
```

Which prints `tick tick tick`. From your code's point of view, you just added a new form to the language. From the interpreter's point of view, there was never anything new — just a loop.

```
$ motoi eval \"(define-syntax repeat (syntax-rules () ((_ n body ...) (let loop ((i 0)) (when (< i n) body ... (loop (+ i 1))))))) (repeat 3 (display \\\"tick \\\"))\"
tick tick tick
```

## Multiple body forms

The `...` lets you have as many body forms as you like:

```
(repeat 3
  (display \"beep-\")
  (display \"boop \"))
```

Expands to:

```
(let loop ((i 0))
  (when (< i 3)
    (display \"beep-\")
    (display \"boop \")
    (loop (+ i 1))))
```

Which prints `beep-boop beep-boop beep-boop `.

The `body ...` in the pattern captures all forms after `n`. The `body ...` in the template spreads them back out. Whatever you put in, comes back out in the same order.

## A macro that captures a name

Here's a subtler one. Suppose you want a `swap!` macro that swaps the values of two variables.

```
(define-syntax swap!
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ a b)
     (let ((tmp a))
       (set! a b)
       (set! b tmp)))))

(define x 1)
(define y 2)
(swap! x y)
(list x y)
;; => (2 1)
```

`swap!` uses a *temporary variable* named `tmp` inside its template. What if the caller happened to have their own variable named `tmp`? Wouldn't the macro's `tmp` clash with the caller's `tmp`?

Not in Scheme. This is where `syntax-rules` earns its reputation: it's *hygienic*. Any local name introduced by a macro is automatically renamed to something unique that can't collide with anything in the caller's code. You never have to think about it. `tmp` inside the macro is a *different variable* than `tmp` outside, even though they share a name in the source.

This hygienic guarantee is a big deal. In older macro systems (like C's `#define`), name collisions between macros and callers were a constant hazard. `syntax-rules` solved that once and for all.

## Recursive macros

Macros can call themselves. Here's a hand-rolled `and`:

```
(define-syntax my-and
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_) #t)
    ((_ x) x)
    ((_ x y ...) (if x (my-and y ...) #f))))
```

Three rules:
- `(my-and)` — no arguments — expands to `#t`. (Empty `and` is true.)
- `(my-and x)` — one argument — expands to just `x`.
- `(my-and x y ...)` — two or more — expands to a conditional that evaluates `x`; if truthy, recursively `my-and`s the rest.

Test:

```
(my-and)              ;; => #t
(my-and 1 2 3)        ;; => 3
(my-and 1 #f 3)       ;; => #f
```

The pattern matcher picks the *first* matching rule from the top. `(my-and 1 2 3)` matches the third rule (it has more than one argument), which expands to `(if 1 (my-and 2 3) #f)`. `(my-and 2 3)` matches the third rule again, expands to `(if 2 (my-and 3) #f)`. `(my-and 3)` matches the second rule, expands to `3`. So `(my-and 1 2 3)` ends up as `(if 1 (if 2 3 #f) #f)` — which evaluates to 3.

That's how `and` is often defined in Scheme itself, more or less.

## `when` and `unless` — the classics

Motoi has both of these built in, but they're two of the simplest useful macros. Let's see:

```
(define-syntax when
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ condition body ...)
     (if condition
         (begin body ...)
         #f))))

(define-syntax unless
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ condition body ...)
     (when (not condition) body ...))))
```

`when` runs the body only if the condition is truthy. If not, returns `#f`. `unless` is `when` with a negated condition — the classic *build a new macro on top of another macro* pattern.

Once you internalize `when` and `unless` and `repeat` and `swap!`, you'll want more. That's Chapter 10.

## What a macro is *not*

A macro is not a function. Two important consequences:

**Arguments aren't evaluated.** In a function call, all arguments are evaluated before the function runs. In a macro use, arguments are just *code fragments* — they're substituted into the template as-is. This is what makes `if`, `when`, `and`, `or`, `cond` work — they can decide *whether* to evaluate their arguments. Functions can't do that.

**Macros don't exist at runtime.** By the time your program runs, all macros have been expanded away. If you `,macroexpand` a form, you can see what it became. But at runtime it's just the expansion — no trace of the macro.

Because of this, some things you can do with functions you can't do with macros:

- You can't pass a macro as an argument to another function.
- You can't put a macro in a list.
- You can't `apply` a macro.

If you want first-class-ness, you want a function. If you want new syntax, you want a macro.

## `,expand` — see what the macro made

Motoi's REPL has a shortcut for seeing the expansion. In your terminal:

```
$ motoi repl
motoi> (define-syntax repeat
         (syntax-rules ()
           ((_ n body ...)
            (let loop ((i 0))
              (when (< i n)
                body ...
                (loop (+ i 1)))))))
motoi> ,expand (repeat 3 (display \"a\"))
(let loop ((i 0))
  (when (< i 3)
    (display \"a\")
    (loop (+ i 1))))
```

You can inspect any macro use this way. If a macro is misbehaving, `,expand` is the debugger. Show me what you *think* the code became — usually that's enough to spot the bug.

## Small, useful macros to have around

```
;; Do these things, ignore the result. Sometimes clearer than begin.
(define-syntax do-things
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ body ...) (begin body ... #f))))

;; Do these things, return the first form's value.
(define-syntax do-and-return-first
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ first-form body ...)
     (let ((result first-form))
       body ...
       result))))

;; Assertion macro.
(define-syntax assert
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ pred) (unless pred (display \"assertion failed\") (newline)))))

(assert (= (+ 1 1) 2))   ;; silent — passes
(assert (= (+ 1 1) 3))   ;; prints \"assertion failed\"
```

Each of these could be a function, sort of, but wouldn't behave right — functions would evaluate all arguments up-front. Macros can defer evaluation, which is exactly what `assert` needs (only evaluate the predicate if we're checking it) and what `do-and-return-first` needs (evaluate the body forms in order and return the *first* one, not the last).

## What you know now

- A macro is a code transformation that runs before evaluation.
- `define-syntax` + `syntax-rules` define macros.
- Each rule has a pattern (matches shape) and a template (rewrites into this).
- `_` is the macro name in the pattern.
- Pattern variables — any names besides `_` — are bound to whatever code appears there.
- `...` in a pattern matches zero-or-more forms. `...` in the template splats them out.
- Macros are *hygienic* — local names introduced by the macro don't collide with the caller's.
- Macros can be recursive — call themselves for smaller cases.
- Motoi's REPL has `,expand` to see what a macro produced.
- Macros aren't functions: no first-class-ness, no arg evaluation.

## Try before you turn the page

1. Write a macro `swap-print!` that swaps two variables and prints the new values on separate lines. Test on `x` and `y`.

2. Write a macro `times` that takes a count and a body and runs the body that many times without exposing an index. `(times 3 (display \"a\"))` should print `aaa`. Hint: it's `repeat` without the `i`.

3. Write a macro `if-let` — takes `((name value))` and a then-branch and an else-branch. Binds `name` to `value`; if truthy, runs the then; else runs the else. `(if-let ((x (get-thing))) (use x) 'nothing)`.

4. Rewrite Chapter 3's nested-loop grid painter with a macro `for-cell` that takes `(rows cols body ...)` and runs the body with `row` and `col` bound each iteration. Warning — hygiene matters here; think about whether `row` and `col` should be introduced by the macro or captured from the caller.

5. Use `,expand` in the REPL to see the expansion of your `repeat` and `unless` calls. Confirm they're what you expect.

## What's next

Chapter 10: **real macros — a beat DSL**. We're going to build a little language *on top of* Scheme, using macros. `(beat 1 (kick) 2 (kick snare) 3 (kick) 4 (kick snare))` will read like sheet music and run like a drum machine. Macros are how languages grow. Chapter 10 is where that becomes obvious.")
